nderstanding of the biogeographic patterns and dynamics. He provides an overview of the basic theory, concepts, and analytical tools of island biogeography. Also discussed are island relaxation to lower equilibrium species numbers post-isolation, plant distributions variously limited by island area, isolation and climatic differences, adaptation to local abiotic and biotic environments within islands, and the evolution of different island phenotypes. The book concludes with a valuable consideration of equilibrium concepts and of the interplay of coexistence and competition. Certain to challenge, Plants on Islands is among the first books to critically analyze the central tenets of the theory of island biogeography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIsland plantszBritish ColumbiazBarkley Sound Region. 0aPhytogeographyzBritish ColumbiazBarkley Sound Region. 0aPlant communitieszBritish ColumbiazBarkley Sound Region. 0aPlant ecologyzBritish ColumbiazBarkley Sound Region. 0aVegetation dynamicszBritish ColumbiazBarkley Sound Region. 70(DE-601)1047308380(DE-588)4045539-7aPflanzen2gnd 70(DE-601)1057188740(DE-588)4128227-9aInsel2gnd 70(DE-601)2160812700(DE-588)4424641-9aInselbiogeografie2gnd 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  abarkley sound.  abritish columbia.  aevolution of different island phenotypes.  aisland biogeographic theory.  aisolation and climatic differences.  ameticulous.  amore than two hundred islands.  aplant distributions.  aplants on continental islands.  astudy of biogeography of island plants.  athorough.  athree hundred species of plants.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024729140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093272240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/is